874653,0.05539249,-0.00510844,0.00055660,0.04431450,-0.01309807,-0.01510318,0.02721140,0.04630214,-0.01396852,0.10002740,-0.02579529,0.03247478,-0.03435610,0.02652956,0.00356305,0.01573895,-0.02844211,-0.02878478,-0.00425857,-0.04710515,-0.04103453,0.01903240,-0.04862804,-0.09131508,-0.01068547,-0.03071210,-0.01562430,-0.03849944,-0.03910555,0.02729553,-0.02507877,0.02933766,-0.00516517,-0.00131022,0.05129994,-0.04716497,0.02012823,0.02249340,0.00161137,-0.02059442,0.00910001,0.04301341]',E'Scoped Beans as Dependencies\n\nAlso, scoped proxies are not the only way to access beans from shorter scopes in a\nlifecycle-safe fashion. You may also declare your injection point (that is, the\nconstructor or setter argument or autowired field) as `ObjectFactory<MyTargetBean>`,\nallowing for a `getObject()` call to retrieve the current instance on demand every\ntime it is needed -- without holding on to the instance or storing it separately.','{"source": "spring-framework", "version": "7", "language": "java", "title": "Factory Scopes.Adoc", "section_title": "factory-scopes.adoc", "url": "https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-framework/blob/main/framework-docs/modules/ROOT/pages/core/beans/factory-scopes.adoc", "topics": "spring,framework,factory,scopes.adoc", "categories": "java,enterprise,ioc,web"}');
