4,0.20976371,0.04372093,-0.01298052,0.06451822,0.09466732,0.01152623,0.02515435,0.00144602,0.03292182,-0.03184000,0.04279142,-0.02889833,0.03447517,0.01641827,0.05358274,-0.03777352,-0.01102304,0.01075325,-0.04145193,-0.01582381,-0.00771782,-0.01840753,0.04257797,0.01522972,-0.03009722,-0.05532113,-0.06480775,0.02366164,-0.00337645,-0.06801732,-0.02107350,-0.04145468,0.05060912,0.03143393,-0.03293932,0.03890950,-0.03727261,0.00390919,0.04259264,0.01334652,0.04589368,0.07748505,0.04758189]',E'Testing\n\n:page-section-summary-toc: 1\n\nThis chapter covers Spring''s support for integration testing and best practices for unit\ntesting. The Spring team advocates test-driven development (TDD). The Spring team has\nfound that the correct use of inversion of control (IoC) certainly does make both unit\nand integration testing easier (in that the presence of setter methods and appropriate\nconstructors on classes makes them easier to wire together in a test without having to\nset up service locator registries and similar structures).','{"source": "spring-framework", "version": "7", "language": "java", "title": "Testing.Adoc", "section_title": "testing.adoc", "url": "https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-framework/blob/main/framework-docs/modules/ROOT/pages/testing.adoc", "topics": "spring,framework,testing.adoc", "categories": "java,enterprise,ioc,web"}');
